description: From Middle English withtaken; equivalent to with- +‎ take.

verbs.description: withtake (third-person singular simple present withtakes, present participle withtaking, simple past withtook, past participle withtaken)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To receive; accept or withstand; (often reflexive) To take along; take with.
examples: […]  and if the people of the said cities and towns will not or are not able to maintain them they shall withtake themselves to other towns and cities within the hundred, or to the town where they were born, and shall there continually abide during their life.
